\begin{tcbProblem}[label={problem:0066:question:Eng}]
	Consider quadratic Diophantine equations of the form:
	\begin{equation*}
		{ x }^{ 2 } \minus D { y }^{ 2 } \equal 1
	\end{equation*}
	For example, when \( D \equal 13 \), the mininal solution in \( x \) is \( { 649 }^{ 2 } \minus 13 \times { 180 }^{ 2 } \equal 1 \).

	It can be assumed that there are no solutions in positive integers when \( D \) is square.

	By finding minimal solutions in \( x \) for \( D \equal \lbrace 2 \mathcomma 3 \mathcomma 5 \mathcomma 6 \mathcomma 7 \rbrace \), we obtain the following:
	\begin{align*}
		{ 3 }^{ 2 } \minus 2 \times { 2 }^{ 2 } &\equal 1 \\%
		{ 2 }^{ 2 } \minus 3 \times { 1 }^{ 2 } &\equal 1 \\%
		{ \textcolor{cudred}{9} }^{ 2 } \minus 5 \times { 4 }^{ 2 } &\equal 1 \\%
		{ 5 }^{ 2 } \minus 6 \times { 2 }^{ 2 } &\equal 1 \\%
		{ 8 }^{ 2 } \minus 7 \times { 3 }^{ 2 } &\equal 1
	\end{align*}
	Hence, by considering minimal solutions in \( x \) for \( D \leq 7 \), the largest \( x \) is obtained when \( D \equal 5 \).

	Find the value of \( D \leq 1000 \) in minimal solutions of \( x \) for which the largest value of \( x \) is obtained.
	\par%
	\hrefOriginalPage{66}%
\end{tcbProblem}
